A model displaying extremely inhomogeneous matter distribution
  in General Relativity 

Elcio Abdalla and Cecilia B. M. H. Chirenti 
 
Instituto de Fisica, Universidade de Sao Paulo

C.P.66.318, CEP 05315-970, Sao Paulo, Brazil. 


 

We consider a toy metric in four dimensional space-time defined in terms
of a recursive hierarchical prescription. The matter distribution turns
out to be extremely inhomogeneous. Surprisingly, for very large samples
the average mass density tends (very slowly) to a constant. There is
no trace of fractal dimension left. 




Although most authors tend to believe that the large scale distribution of
matter should be constant as predicted by Einstein's cosmological
principle there is also a belief that such an
idea should be further checked against observation
. Some authors argued quite convincingly that the
large scale distribution of matter should be fractal, quite the oposite to
that expected by the cosmological principle.
Inhomogeneous cosmological models have been searched by many authors
 
. The fact that detailed maps show quite strong
inhomogeneities has been a motivation for long controversies.

Here, we construct a metric defined in terms of a hierarchy, building an
expectation that the matter distribution obtained from the corresponding
Einstein's Equations are extremely inhomogeneous, contradicting the
cosmological principle, and probably presenting fractality properties,
with a non trivial effective dimension. As it turns out, some of these
conclusions are false, as we shall see.

Our starting point is the diagonal metric defined in terms of a
distribution of points. A point in space-time is only defined at the
integers. Indeed, we expect that a metric describing a fractal
distribution cannot be continuous at any point, therefore it can only be
defined on a discrete set. With this motivation in mind, we define, in a
given direction  (either 1, 2 or 3) the distance between two points as
pictorically represented in Fig. 1, with the metric 
g_ =1 & 0 & 0 & 0                         0 & g_11 &0 & 0 
                           0 & 0& g_22 & 0 
                       0 &  0 &   0 &  g_33   ,
where the metric is defined on all integers, depending on their
decomposition in terms of powers of 2, as below,
g_11 (x)&=&a^2k  ,with x = 2^k+1  + 2^k -1

g_22 (y)&=&a^2l  ,with y = 2^l+1  + 2^l -1


g_33 (x)&=&a^2m  ,with z = 2^m+1  + 2^m -1.Above, ,  and  are nonnegative integers and the metric is defined
as unit when the entry is an even number. This defines the metric (see
Fig. 1). 


